{"cursor":"20141","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n]] microbrewery in Nottingham, England]] A 'barrel', 'cask', or 'tun' is a\nhollow cylindrical container, traditionally made of wooden staves bound by\nwooden or metal hoops. Traditionally, the barrel was a standard size of measure\nreferring to a set capacity or weight of a given commodity. For example, in the\nUK a barrel of beer refers to a quantity of 36 imperial gallons. Wine was\nshipped in barrels of . A small barrel is called a keg.\n\nModern wooden barrels for wine-making are either made of French common oak\n(Quercus robur) and white oak (Quercus petraea) or from American white oak\n(Quercus alba) and have typically these standard sizes: \"Bordeaux type\" and\n\"Cognac type\" . Modern barrels and casks can also be made of aluminum, stainless\nsteel, and different types of plastic, such as HDPE.\n\nSomeone who makes barrels is called a \"barrel maker\" or [[Cooper\n(profession)|cooper]]. Barrels are only one type of cooperage. Other types\ninclude, but are not limited to: buckets, tubs, butter churns, hogsheads,\nfirkins, kegs, kilderkins, tierces, rundlets, puncheons, pipes, tuns, butts,\npins, and breakers.\n\nBarrels have a variety of uses, including storage of liquids such as water and\noil, fermenting wine, arrack and sake, and maturing beverages such as wine,\ncognac, armagnac, sherry, port, whiskey and beer.\n","linknr":642,"url":"Cask","recorded":1362675378,"links":74,"instances":["physics","cask","container","fastener","wine","drink","unit","brandy","unit","wine","volume","wine","politics"],"pdf":["http://www.asm.org/ASM/files/ccLibraryFiles/Filename/000000004753/znw00309000104.pdf"],"categories":["Wine packaging and storage","Beer vessels and serving","Shipping containers","Gardening aids","Food storage containers"],"headings":["History","Uses","Shape","Sizes","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Oak-wine-